SIMPLE: ravishment
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Ravishment
<hw>Rav"ish*ment</hw> <pr>(-m⟦eit⟧nt)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>ravissement</ets>. See <er>Ravish</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of carrying away by force or against
consent; abduction; <as>as, the <ex>ravishment</ex> of children from
their parents, of a ward from his guardian, or of a wife from her
husband</as>.</def> <rj><au>Blackstone.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The state of being ravished; rapture; transport of
delight; ecstasy.</def> <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In whose sight all things joy, with <qex>ravishment</qex>⟦br⟧
Attracted by thy beauty still to gaze.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The act of ravishing a woman; rape.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ravissant</ent>⟦br⟧
